Maybe a fisheye lens for a nesting box is a bit too much of a good thing.
You never learn.
I should have known better, since I already built one with a "normal" lens before.
I'll write more about it this weekend once I've installed the second one.
Let's just say the birds will have a better internet connection than I did in 2015.
At least that's the plan.
The box, which already has a nest, consumes a lot of WLAN data.
With the other one it will be a bit more difficult, since it can go online.
Okay, I hung up the new nesting box today. This is how it looks in its new place in the garden.
But let's go back a bit. No one is asking: "What exactly is inside?"
At the top is one of these ESP32 camera boards with a camera equipped with a fisheye lens and an IR LED, which I got from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for the strange shape of this plastic box is the swiveling side wall of the nesting box. I bought it like that and couldn't change it, so I had to build around it.
Since there's no electricity in the garden, the whole thing is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here is a picture of the panel.
In the gray box that is hanging on the side of the nesting box is the battery.
Once it is charged, I have a runtime of about 4 hours.
I'll call that a feature. This way the birds also get some privacy.
At first, I wasn't sure if the internet in our garden would be sufficient for this setup. The old access points that I replaced last autumn wouldn't have been enough.
But the new ones cover this area very well.
That's almost a pity, because I had planned to install a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and point it downwards into the garden.
Maybe I will do that still, if I install more nest boxes with cameras. Especially in areas that are further away from the house, I probably need that.
Now the camera is offline and I don't know why. It only turned off one hour after sunset.
Perhaps the battery didn't charge any further three hours before sunset because there wasn't enough light.
Or something less than half a day was not enough to fully charge the battery.
I guess I have to wait and see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have telemetry for the battery. I might have to change that in the future.
Generally, a few more sensors would be a good thing, I think.
And maybe a battery that is at least theoretically capable of keeping it running through the night.
Oh, and another lens.
Fisheye is quite exaggerated.
But I'm already looking for parts at Digikey so that I can build my own board specifically for that.
Or maybe not. We'll see.
And he is still offline.
Great.
According to the actual solar panels on the house, we only have about 90 minutes of proper sunlight.
Let's wait another one or two hours to see what happens – or also not.
Still offline.
It's never easy, after all.
It turned out that on the USB-C breakout I used to connect the charger, the 5 V and GND were swapped on the silkscreen.
I swapped the cables and now the charging indicator is lighting up.
The ESP did not go online immediately. Let's wait a few minutes.
An hour has passed and it is still offline.
It looks like it is restarting and triggering a Tasmota reset function.
I think the panel is just useless. I have now ordered a larger one and hope that this one will work.
Take a look at what I found in my workshop.
A 24-V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is already so low (and is partially obscured by a tree), that the value practically drops to zero as soon as I switch the device on.
I'll probably have to wait until tomorrow to see if this setup is sufficient or if I need the better panel I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the panel in 2021 and it is supposed to deliver 12 V at a maximum of 1.2 A.
So either something is wrong with the panel or with my multimeter, or the specifications have been changed.
Good news!
You have changed the data and the ones I have are wrong.
The old as well as the new listing title call it a 12 V 10-W panel.
That's why I never delete old e-mails.
Oh look! The thing went offline about an hour ago, and then back online again for about half a minute.
Maybe the panel just charged the battery long enough for 38 seconds of runtime. It only took a bit more than two hours for that.
Guess what: Today it's cloudy. Therefore, I'm not sure whether the (probably broken) solar panel will manage to generate enough electricity at all.
Let's wait and see.
Update: I have installed the new panel and now it seems to be working.
It could still fail as soon as the sun sets, but let's give it a chance.
Fun fact: I use the Ping integration in Home Assistant to see whether it is online or not.
The average connection time is 102 ms. Not particularly good, but also not crazy bad.
